1. Abstract¶

As big metropolitan areas continue to grow there is a need to reduce vehicle congestion for convenience and safety reasons but also as a means of cutting back on emissions and meeting cliamte change adaptation goals. An increasingly popular solution to this problem has been the deployment of bikeshares in cities across the country. This project will look specifically at bikeshare data from San Francisco along with contemporary weather data. Using machine learning methods this project aims to see how weather and time factors (hour of day, day of week, etc.) trip duration. This will help city commuters who want to bike commute for economic or environmental plan their trips better.

Here I will load in both weather and bikeshare datasets. Both were found on Kaggle at the following links:

  • Weather: https://www.kaggle.com/selfishgene/historical-hourly-weather-data

# Format ride start/end times as dates
trips['start_date'] = pd.to_datetime(trips.start_date,format = '%m/%d/%Y %H:%M')
trips['end_date'] = pd.to_datetime(trips.end_date,format = '%m/%d/%Y %H:%M')
# Calculate the length of each trip
trips['duration'] = trips.end_date - trips.start_date
# Truncate start times to hour precision to match with weather data
trips['start_hour'] = trips['start_date'].dt.floor('h')
# Filter out trips that started and ended at the same station
trips = trips[trips.start_station_id != trips.end_station_id]
# Convert trip duration from timedelta to integer (in minutes)
trips['duration'] = trips.duration.apply(lambda x:x.value/(60000000000))

These plots are telling for a few reasons. It appears clear that these bikes are mostly used for work commuting, as their use peaks during typical travel hours (early morning and early evening) and weekdays.

Interestingly, the average commute time appears inversely related to the count. The highest usage hours have the lowest average times. This could possibly be due to people biking more directly on their work commutes and taking longer when they bike for leisure or other non-commute related reasons.

We can also look at the split between customers and subscribers. Customers pay for each ride they take, while subscribes pay a recurring charge to ride as much as they'd like.

Unfortunately, we are not given data on individual users to determine their ride frequency. In lieu of that I am selecting only subscribers for analysis. The rationale for this is that people who have daily commutes will be subscribers because it is more cost effective.

Moving forward from EDA:

The exploratory data analysis revealed the peak times and most popular days for commuting were Mon-Fri during mid-morning and early evening hours. Since the goal of this project is to help predict commute times, I think it would make sense to limit our data to these times. People using bikes for leisure are presumably not as interested in their commute times so they may take longer/not bike anywhere specific, skewing the data. Similarly, we've identified the most popular routes, these could also be used to filter the data to make the dataset more manageable in size for modeling.

4. Feature Engineering¶

For feature engineering I'm going to normalize the weather variables using the scale method in sklearn. For Timestamp data I'll extract hour, day of week, and month of year to serve as their own features. Normalizing the weather data will improve the models predictive ability by removing the effect large outliers might have. By pulling out individual time features it will allow me how different time scales affect trip time.

Since the weather data is taken at hourly intervals I'll have to bucketize the bikeshare data into matching intervals. I may also only select for trips along the most popular routes as a way to pare down the data into a more manageable sample. This will help boost performance time of the model while still retaining the most pertinent information.

Trip durations are given to the second, however in planning a commute that type of precision isn't necessary so I plan to round trip durations to the nearest minute. This should improve the models performance as well since it will not be required to predict super precisely.

5. Model Selection¶

To measure the error of the model I used mean absolute percent error (MAPE). This is a good metric for this particular problem because it gives a concrete scale for how far off a commute prediction is on average. For instance a 10 minute commute with a 25% MAPE means that the model predicts a commute between 7.5 and 12.5 minutes typically.

In [30]:
# code adapted from: https://gist.github.com/amanahuja/6315882
def mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred):
    y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
    return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

After tuning the parameters I was able to improve the performance from ~35% to ~27%. This error is slightly higher than I was aiming for but considering we're predicting commute times, it doesn't need to be right on. What this does show though, is that weather does play a role in commute times and that using past data we can use that data to predict future commutes. This could be useful in applications like Google Maps, which could use weather forecasts to improve their commute estimates.
